  <li id="comment-43706" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2015/02/et-voila/#comment-43706"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-02-18T03:47:45-05:00">Wednesday, February 18, 2015 at 3:47 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hello <br />Darling photos. I have been a potter for 35 years and made many cups and dishes with/for my children. Favorite thing I made was a complete tea set for Paddington Bear..many hours of tea parties. i look firward to making pots in my studio with my grandchildren.<br />Just as a note of caution I noticed that the glaze you used probably contains copper and it may be a bit underfired. Check out this article on food safety and metallic oxides. check with your instructor as to the composition of the glaze and perhaps just do the vinegar test for copper solubility.When I taught ceramic glaze chemistry at an art school I always discussed this with my students. But, I never purchased my classes, always made them with raw minerals and oxides so I could control the result. If your instructor uses purchased glazes perhaps check with them. In my work  I did not use copper on any food surfaces that would come into contact with acid and if I did, I always told clients that they musn&#39;t allow acidic food to be in contact with the copper surface for extended periods  of time.  .<a href="http://digitalfire.com/4sight/education/are_your_glazes_food_safe_or_are_they_leachable_12.html" rel="nofollow ugc">http://digitalfire.com/4sight/education/are_your_glazes_food_safe_or_are_they_leachable_12.html</a><br />Sorry to be Debbie Downer!<br />Linda</p>
    </div>

